This standard is all about selecting probability distributions as models for situations. Students are expected to know about the normal, Poisson, triangular and uniform distributions and their features, so they can consider if they could be good models for the situation. If students were presented with a situation to model where the data was discrete, and it was not suitable to model with Poisson, then students would need to consider how/if they could use the normal, triangular or uniform distributions as models (e.g. by modifying it in some way through continuity corrections, possibly even truncation). This is all in keeping with the standard, assessment specifications and the senior secondary guide.

&nbsp;

So many of the practice problems I see for continuity corrections, however, are focused on calculations e.g. finding the probability of something and whether to use the lower or upper bound for a continuous interval. The probability distribution is presented as the reality rather than the model e.g. the volume of toothpaste in a tube IS normally distributed, when the normal distribution is being used as a model for the volume of toothpaste in a tube. For example, Jake, you have this question in your online practice problems (and others similar to it): The number of cotton buds in a box is normally distributed with a mean of 200 and a standard deviation of 30. Calculate the probability the number of cotton buds in the box is more than 150. Clearly this is a made up question (we all do this!) but just think about the parameters of that model and what that means in reality. My point here is that these made up word problems, designed just to test continuity correction, are harmful as they interfere with important modelling ideas. The first consideration should be whether any model makes sense in the first place, and if you have data from the situation, what you can learn from that data to help you consider suitable models.

&nbsp;

Id hope that if continuity corrections were assessed in the exam, focus would be placed on selecting the model first. We all know thats enough of a challenge for students in the first place! For example, the 2014 exam has a question Q3(b) about donations. Students need to consider a model for the situation, with several accepted in the schedule and no mention of continuity corrections.

&nbsp;

This wording clouds the important idea that the probability distributions we are using are only models, are probably wrong, are not exact. Also, Im finding it hard to believe that the number of cotton buds in a box is normally distributed with a mean of 200 and a standard deviation of 30. Given that you are saying that the cotton buds are IN the box, if I use 99.7% limits (e.g. 4 sds) then I would have to believe the manufacturer is totally cool with variation between 80 and 320 cotton buds per box. In reality for packing stuff into boxes scenarios, models used are truncated, skewed or symmetric but with very small variation between outcomes or with acceptance that items fall out of the box (loss of product).

&nbsp;

Id be much happier if instead, For example, give students some real discrete data from two situations (e.g. small boxes of smarties and small packets of raisins), and then ask them to develop a graphical model for each (e.g. a bar chart with proportions for each outcome  the number of smarties/raisins per box  under the model they have selected) for the situation using one of the continuous probability distributions listed above (e.g. triangular). Once they have this, they can use it to answer questions about probabilities using the model or whatever. Hopefully through this learning process they will (a) appreciate that if they are working with data to form their model then their model is not exact anyway (see my work/tool to help) so they do not have THE (true) probability and (b) in the case of situations with small sample spaces (not that many discrete outcomes) not using a continuity correction is more of an issue than in situations with large sample spaces

&nbsp;

